What is the difference between merge and rebase — when to use each?
merge will take the starting point of both branches as reference, combine all changes of both branches and merge with current one. rebase will run all the commits of the target branch one by one over the current one.

What does git reset --soft, --mixed, --hard do?
--soft will uncommit the latest commit but all the changes will more to staging area
--mixed will uncommit the latest commit and also remove all the changes from the staging area so we should add everything again one by one
--hard will uncommit and delete all the changes including in the local

What is git revert and why is it safer than reset on shared branches?
git revert will uncommit the changes but without affecting the history. like it will create a new commit that has changes that uncommits the latest commit on top of it.

What is git reflog and when would it save you?
reflog will have all changes and deleted changes and everything for 30 days. even if we delete something by mistake we can recover it using reflog. its like a black box for git.

What does git stash do internally?
git stash doesn't commit any changes instead it stores all changes as temporary in the git. we can add as many changes we want using stash. if those are required we can apply the particular stash and add it to staging area. or just use stash pop to delete the stash.

What is a fast-forward merge?
fast forward merge is where if there is no changes in one branch from the branching point and when we tried to merge it with another, it will just move the pointer to the latest commit of the target branch.

What does squash do in interactive rebase?
squash will combine git commits. we can use git rebase-i HEAD~3 to combine last 3 commits. 
or git merge --squash target_branch to squash all commits.

What is the difference between GitFlow and trunk-based development?
GitFlow uses long lived branches like feature, release, hotfix, develop, master/main to manage the project. it is used where the project requires scheduled releases and incremental updates. 
trunk-based just make changes in the main branch and if required short lived branches are created. 

What is a Pull Request and what problem does it solve?
pull request is used when we have new features or changes in separate branch and want to merge it with the main after approval from the team with code review.

What algorithm does git bisect use and why is it efficient?
it uses binary search algorithm where we start the bisect and mark good and bad commits, it will point to the middle commit first and ask if its good or bad. subsequently it will do the same till the last bad is found which would be the origin of the defect.

