What does Cloud Composer manage that standalone Airflow doesn't?
the cloud composer authentication issues(secret key), yml configurations, rbac things, more refined dag serialization, auto scaling, computing, network, auto installs the dependencies in requirements.txt.

Why is PostgreSQL better than SQLite for Airflow in production?
SQLite doesn't run on servers and is very basic compared to PostgreSQL. including the mvcc and many things postgres is better and for airflow postgres is the gold standard.

How are DAGs deployed in Composer vs minikube Airflow?
in minikube, we mount the local dags path to the /opt/airflow/dags. everytime we start the deployment, it will take the dags with the mounted folder. or we can exec into the container and copy files while the app is running. 
in composer, a bucket is created automatically by the composer. we have dags folder inside and we can copy it directly there. it will check the folder every 1-2 mins and update the dags.

What is trigger_rule=ALL_DONE and why did we use it on delete_cluster?
if we give ALL_SUCCESS, the cluster would get deleted only of all are successful. and will still be running costing credits. ALL_DONE will delete the cluster even if some tasks are failed. 

What is {{ ds_nodash }} and why did we use it in the cluster name?
normal ds will give logical date and time with hyphens. ds_nodash will elimiate those hypens. this will give cleaner name for the cluster in our use.

Why do we use ephemeral clusters instead of permanent ones?
so that it will be deleted after job is done and computing and storage costs will be saved. also for scaling this is better.

Why can't dbt run inside Composer? What's the production solution?
dbt and airflow have a lot of version mismatch complexities. we could make it work with some effort but it is not much reliable. so we can use cloud run to make dbt task work after composer complete its job.

What is the difference between DataprocCreateClusterOperator and DataprocSubmitJobOperator?
DataprocCreateClusterOperator - an api to create cluster with the given cluster config.
DataprocSubmitJobOperator - an api to sumbit the job config with task id (pyspark job or hadoop)

Full GCP pipeline self-test:
What happens in each step
first, we setup the gcp bucket to store the python files and raw data. then we configure the composer with dependencies like pyarrow, pandas and gcp related dependencies. once it sets up, the composer creates  its own bucket in the cloud storage with relevant folders. we then store our dag file in the dags folder and open the airflow UI. we trigger the dag and it  will run the tasks according to the dag file including cleaning raw data, doing pyspark transformation in it using dataproc clusters, loading the result to the bigquery.

Which GCP service handles it
composer which support airflow implementation.

Where data lives after each step
we have the raw data in the bucket. During ingestion, the python file take in raw data, cleans it and save output in the bucket (as we mentioned in the file), then pyspark cluster will take the cleaned data back from the bucket and manipulate and load the output to the bucket again. then the stored output is then loaded to bigquery.

What would fail if you skipped each step
if ingestion fails, pyspark can't  find the cleaned data or will manipulate old cleaned ones. 
if pyspark fails, the bigquery loading doesn't happen or  it moves the old data again.
if loading to bigquery fails, the data wouldn't be in the bigquery and we can't do queries there or any dbt manipulations.

What is the nanosecond timestamp bug and how did you fix it?
the pandas function store the output file with the nanosecond timestamp. but the  spark only support microseconds timestamp. so we force pandas to store as microseconds using "coerce_timestamps="us""

